220/00200290392/1907111401/0715.pdf", "segment_count": 8, "url": "https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn87093220/1907-11-14/ed-1/", "word_coordinates": "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service"}], "segment_id": "/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_hoh_ver01/data/sn87093220/00200290392/1907111401/0715.xml", "segments": [{"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn87093220/1907-11-14/ed-1/?sp=1"], "batch": ["wa_hoh_ver01"], "campaigns": [], "composite_location": ["0/united states/", "1/united states/washington/", "2/united states/washington/grays harbor/", "3/united states/washington/grays harbor/aberdeen/"], "contributor": ["washington state library; olympia, wa"], "date": "1907-11-14", "dates": ["1907-11-14"], "description": ["The HERALD is the Most Widely Read Paper on Crays Harbor ABERDEEN HERALD VOL XXII SKIES AHE CLEARING FINANCiAL CLOUDS ROLLING BY IN THE EAST The Mississippi Valley Lumberman of November S on the Financial Situation in That Region A Plan Proposed to Eliminate Peeling ot Distrust of Banks During the past week there lias been a considerable change in the j business outlook A week ago there was much gloom in spite of the fact that clearheaded people knew there was nothing in general conditions throughout the country that usually accompany business depression or causes it Today the feeling is hope ful because that fact has been rec ognized by most people and because business has in a measure adjusted itself to the new order inaugurated by the banks Money is more plen tiful and there is a greater disposi tion to permit it to circulate The prompt action of the secretary of the treasury in depositing government money in the large financial centers and the large imports of gold from abroad have supplied currency for the necessary cash transactions in the east and the equally prompt ac tion on the part of the secretary of the treasury in"], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2024-04-26T11:27:00.015Z", "group": ["ndnp/wa"